<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920313-0133</DOCNO><DOCID>920313-0133.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Corning Inc.:   Concern, Asahi Glass Agree   To Pay Air Pollution Fine</HL><DATE>03/13/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   GLW J.AHG</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>CONTAINERS andamp; PACKAGING (CTR)DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Corning Inc., Asahi Glass America Inc. and their jointventure, Corning Asahi Video Products, agreed to pay a $1.8million air pollution fine, the U.S. Environmental ProtectionAgency said. The fine will be paid by Corning Asahi, Corningsaid.   Corning Asahi's glass plants in State College andCharleroi, Pa., exceeded emissions standards for arsenic, theEPA said. Most of the violations, including using arsenic atthe Charleroi plants without regulatory approval, took placebefore October 1988, when the plants were owned solely byCorning.</LP><TEXT>   Under terms of a consent decree, the companies also agreedto use computers to monitor machinery that controls arsenicemissions and to maintain the machinery at least once a year.Corning Asahi supplies glass to television tube makers andCorning Inc. is a glass, specialty materials and opticalfibers concern. Both are based in Corning, N.Y. Asahi Glassis the U.S. unit of Tokyo's Asahi Glass Co.</TEXT></DOC>